Detectives have commenced investigations at the Dusit complex which was attacked by terrorists on Tuesday, Interior CS Fred Matiangi has said. Matiang'i said the first phase was to neutralize the terrorists and have now embarked on the second phase targeting to start a criminal process. “I came here to thank men and women in uniform for the great work. The operation was executed well. Phase one is over and we now enter phase two and Dusit remains a crime scene. The public will not be allowed in until detectives have done their part,” Matiangi said. The CS was addressing journalists at the scene on Wednesday morning. The media briefing was also attended by officials from the police, Kenya Defence Forces and other humanitarian organizations. At 10 am, an injured recce officer who had been shot both legs was also taken to hospital in an ambulance. “We thank the security forces who have worked tirelessly in an effort to evacuate the hostages while risking their lives,” Matiangi said. Matiangi said the attack lasted 18 hours. “We are still compiling the details and we will tell the total number of those killed. 18 people were injured and over 700 people evacuated,” Kenya Red Cross Society Secretary-General Abbas Gullet told journalists. The last explosion was heard at 6 am today. Read: Riverside Drive attack: All 6 attackers killed - police source “I thank the hotel for helping us. They first asked us to go to the first floor and into our rooms. They closed all the doors and they kept updating us what was going on outside,” a French citizen Mamadou Dia said. “Terrorism is a global problem and it cannot stop me from visiting this beautiful country called Kenyaa” he added. Dia said they were attacked after having lunch with three friends who were all rescued. Also read: Cops cordon off Ruaka estate where suspected Riverside terrorist lived Click here for the latest political news